                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d960">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">860h.01/3–145: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador to the Yugoslav Government in Exile</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Patterson</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">at London</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-03-03T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >March 3, 1945—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Yugos 31. Reurtel 41 March 1.<note n="98" xml:id="d960fn98">Not printed; in his
                        telegram Ambassador Patterson reported that Mr. Stevenson, the British
                        Ambassador to Yugoslavia, told him that he was instructed to press King
                        Peter to accept the regents immediately, and he asked Mr. Paterson to cable
                        Washington for similar instructions. Stevenson added that “if King does not
                        agree by this week end, his consent will be presumed and the United
                        Government formed.” (860h.01/3–145)</note> You may advise Stevenson that we
                    are not disposed to press the King with respect to his selections for the
                    Regency Council, since we consider that your standing instructions fully express
                    our views.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
